    "encrypted": "false",
    "long_instructions": "A social media analyst wants to analyze user demographics and create a visual representation of platform usage across different age groups. The analyst needs to check if any social media platform has duplicate percentage values across age groups, as duplicate values may indicate common trends in user engagement.\r\n\r\nThey have the following values:\r\n\r\n<pre style=\"background-color: #333333; color: white;\">\r\nRow 1: 22, 29, 39, 47\r\nRow 2: 41, 38, 37, 37\r\nRow 3: 23, 21, 18, 12\r\nRow 4: 15, 12, 6, 4\r\n</pre>\r\n\r\nwhere each row represents ages 18-29, ages 30-49, ages 50-64, and ages 65 and up, respectively. Each column represents the percentages of users on Facebook, YouTube, Twitter, and Instagram, respectively.\r\n\r\n✅ **TO DO #1:** In the <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black;\">SocialMediaScene</code> class, write the <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black;\">hasDuplicatePercentages()</code> method to determine if any social media platform has duplicate percentage values across the age groups.\r\n\r\n1. Traverse each column in the <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black;\">percentages</code> array.\r\n2. Compare every percentage in the column with every other percentage in the same column.\r\n3. If any duplicate is found, return <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black;\">true</code>.\r\n4. If no duplicates are found after checking all columns, return <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black;\">false</code>.\r\n\r\n✅ **TO DO #2:** In the <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black;\">TheaterRunner</code> class, call the <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black;\">hasDuplicatePercentages()</code> method and print the result to indicate whether any duplicate values were found.\r\n\r\n<div style=\"background-color: #E0D1EC; border: 1px solid #9660bf; border-radius: 5px; font-size: 1.1em; padding: 15px; margin-bottom: 10px;\">\r\n💡 <strong>TIP:</strong> Check out the <strong>Help & Tips</strong> tab ⬆️ for help with traversing a two-dimensional (2D) array in column-major order.\r\n</div>",
